\subsection{Methane}
Our aim is find an equation set with a similar functional form to the carbon cycle that can reproduce the behaviour of current atmospheric models of methane. Since the predominant mechanism for the removal of methane is oxidation by the OH radical within the troposphere, we employ a single (state dependent) decay timescale by setting $a_1 = 1$ and $a_{2,3,4} = 0$ in \ref{eq1}. The state dependence of our carbon cycle model can be applied almost identically to methane, resulting in a parametric model for methane atmospheric lifetime similar to Holmes et al. (2012). However, we find that a term proportional to atmospheric concentration is required in \ref{eq3} to well-reproduce the results found by Holmes et al. due to the negative feedback between methane abundance and tropospheric OH. This results in our final formulation for the universal alpha variable,

\begin{equation} \label{eq4}
\alpha(t) = g_0 \text{sinh}\Big(\frac{r_0 + r_CC_{acc}(t) + r_TT(t) + r_AC(t)}{g_1}\Big).
\end{equation}

